{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.32,0.02,0.11,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7660"},{"type":"tags","id":"7871"},{"type":"tags","id":"7875"},{"type":"tags","id":"8540"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18564"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia is characterised by the accumulation of mature-appearing but immunologically incompetent lymphocytes in blood, bone marrow, and lymphoid tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common clinical finding in symptomatic chronic lymphocytic leukaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphadenopathy","Splenomegaly","Hepatomegaly","Night sweats","Bruising"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common clinical finding, present in approximately 80% of symptomatic patients. The lymph nodes are typically non-tender, firm, and mobile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in about 50% of patients but usually develops later in the disease course\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E is less common than splenomegaly and typically occurs in advanced disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENight sweats\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the B symptoms that indicate advanced or progressive disease but are not typically present at diagnosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBruising\u003C/strong\u003E may occur due to thrombocytopenia but is not a common presenting feature\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany patients are asymptomatic at diagnosis, with the condition discovered incidentally on routine blood tests showing lymphocytosis \u003E5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L. The clinical course is highly variable, with some patients remaining stable for years without requiring treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia is often asymptomatic and discovered incidentally on routine blood tests.","Lymphadenopathy is the most common clinical finding in symptomatic chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, present in 80% of cases.","The diagnosis requires sustained lymphocytosis \u003E5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L with characteristic immunophenotype."],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Mukkamalla SKR, Taneja A, Malipeddi D, et al. Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia. [Updated 2023 Mar 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470433/","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T21:20:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T21:23:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"